#=GF CC   This family of phage Cox proteins is expressed by Enterobacteria
#=GF CC   phages. The Cox protein is a 79-residue basic protein with a
#=GF CC   predicted strong helix-turn-helix DNA-binding motif. It inhibits
#=GF CC   integrative recombination and it activates site-specific
#=GF CC   excision of the HP1 genome from the Haemophilus influenzae
#=GF CC   chromosome, Hp1. Cox appears to function as a tetramer. Cox
#=GF CC   binding sites consist of two direct repeats of the consensus
#=GF CC   motif 5'-GGTMAWWWWA, one Cox tetramer binding to each motif. Cox
#=GF CC   binding interferes with the interaction of HP1 integrase with
#=GF CC   one of its binding sites, IBS5. This competition is central to
#=GF CC   directional control. Both Cox binding sites are needed for full
#=GF CC   inhibition of integration and for activating excision, because
#=GF CC   it plays a positive role in assembling the nucleoprotein
#=GF CC   complexes that produce excisive recombination, by inducing the
#=GF CC   formation of a critical conformation in those complexes [2].
